is denying us air cover.

472
01:05:34,518 --> 01:05:36,395
A disgrace, a fucking disaster.

473
01:05:36,478 --> 01:05:39,148
No, look, the thing is, you see,
I'm expected back, you see.

474
01:05:39,231 --> 01:05:42,985
There's over 300,000 men on this beach,
Private. You'll have to wait your turn.

475
01:05:43,068 --> 01:05:47,447
Just be grateful you're not wounded.
I've orders to leave the wounded behind.

476
01:05:47,990 --> 01:05:52,911
No, no, no, leave it, guv! Never trust a sailor
on dry land. You're best off out of it.

477
01:06:07,384 --> 01:06:08,719
That's not right.

478
01:06:33,410 --> 01:06:34,495
Christ.

479
01:06:41,877 --> 01:06:43,754
Can you hear me, laddies?

480
01:06:43,837 --> 01:06:46,173
I'm coming home!

481
01:07:44,857 --> 01:07:49,444
Take from our souls
the strain and stress

482
01:07:49,528 --> 01:07:53,866
And let our ordered lives confess

483
01:07:53,949 --> 01:07:58,120
The beauty of Thy peace

484
01:07:58,203 --> 01:08:03,125
The beauty of Thy peace

485
01:08:03,584 --> 01:08:08,213
Breathe through the heats of our desire

486
01:08:08,297 --> 01:08:12,593
Thy coolness and Thy balm

487
01:08:12,759 --> 01:08:17,097
Let sense be numb, let flesh retire

488
01:08:17,181 --> 01:08:21,518
Speak through the earthquake, wind and fire

489
01:08:21,602 --> 01:08:25,856
O still, small voice of calm

490
01:08:56,512 --> 01:08:57,596
Guv'nor.

491
01:09:01,433 --> 01:09:03,852
I have to get something to drink.

492
01:09:03,936 --> 01:09:06,480
You need one. You're grey.

493
01:09:06,563 --> 01:09:09,399
He's gone all grey, can you see?

494
01:09:25,415 --> 01:09:27,167
There. Come on.

495
01:09:29,378 --> 01:09:31,046
All I want's a cup of tea now.

496
01:09:48,355 --> 01:09:50,816
What the fuck you doing?

497
01:10:15,591 --> 01:10:21,472
I'm coming home!
Laddie, I'm coming home!

498
01:10:24,391 --> 01:10:30,814
Fuck 'em all! Fuck 'em all!
The long and the short and the tall

499
01:10:30,898 --> 01:10:35,736
Fuck all the Sergeants and WO1s
Fuck all the corporals

500
01:10:35,819 --> 01:10:37,362
and their bastard sons

501
01:10:37,446 --> 01:10:43,744
'Cause we're saying goodbye to them all
As back to their billets they crawl

502
01:10:43,869 --> 01:10:47,247
You'll get no promotion
this side of the ocean

503
01:10:47,331 --> 01:10:51,084
So cheer up, my lads
Fuck 'em all!

504
01:12:01,196 --> 01:12:02,698
Mike!

505
01:12:09,454 --> 01:12:10,914
Mike!

506
01:12:13,375 --> 01:12:14,626
Hold up, guv.

507
01:12:23,218 --> 01:12:24,344
Wait here.

508
01:13:04,760 --> 01:13:06,386
Why don't you sit down?

509
01:13:15,103 --> 01:13:17,022
It's so hot in here.

510
01:13:17,606 --> 01:13:19,483
Take off your boots.

511
01:13:38,794 --> 01:13:42,506
I have to get back. I promised her.

512
01:13:42,589 --> 01:13:44,800
To put things right.

513
01:13:44,883 --> 01:13:49,138
And she loves me. She's waiting for me.

514
01:13:53,350 --> 01:13:54,393
Oi!

515
01:13:57,729 --> 01:13:58,897
Wait, wait, wait.

516
01:14:00,065 --> 01:14:03,152
Hey, what have you done with your boots?

517
01:14:05,779 --> 01:14:08,407
-Look, you're sure you're feeling all right?
-Never better.

518
01:14:08,490 --> 01:14:12,536
Now I'm wondering whether the beach
really is the best place for dinner.

519
01:14:14,204 --> 01:14:19,251
-I'm not sure, I don't recognise it.
-Dunno.

520
01:14:19,334 --> 01:14:21,545
-This'll do, down here.
-No.

521
01:14:22,671 --> 01:14:25,257
-No, no, it's further on.
-What is?

522
01:14:25,340 --> 01:14:27,551
This place I know, an old cottage
with white clapboards

523
01:14:27,634 --> 01:14:30,220
and blue-painted window frames.

524
01:14:32,097 --> 01:14:36,143
Aw, yes.
That's right, that's where we're going.

525
01:14:36,226 --> 01:14:40,397
-It's close to here.
-We're there. This is it.

526
01:15:03,045 --> 01:15:05,631
Here we are, guv. Down here.

527
01:15:42,376 --> 01:15:45,087
That's all right, guv. That's right.

528
01:15:47,130 --> 01:15:51,677
Get your head down. Get your head down.
There you go.

529
01:16:07,151 --> 01:16:10,112
Tuck yourself in. Keep yourself warm.

530
01:16:17,244 --> 01:16:21,999
Chew on a bit of this. But quiet like,
or they'll all be wanting some.

531
01:16:25,627 --> 01:16:27,713
Try and get some sleep.

532
01:17:59,680 --> 01:18:00,806
Find you.

533
01:18:02,141 --> 01:18:03,392
Love you.

534
01:18:04,184 --> 01:18:05,686
Marry you.

535
01:18:06,520 --> 01:18:08,397
And live without shame.

536
01:18:38,969 --> 01:18:44,850
I love you. Come back. Come back to me.

537
01:18:51,023 --> 01:18:53,192
Bit too much noise, guv'nor.
-What?

538
01:18:55,360 --> 01:18:57,821
-What noise?
-You keep shouting.

539
01:18:57,905 --> 01:19:00,824
-Some of the lads are getting a bit peeved.
-What?

540
01:19:12,961 --> 01:19:17,633
-Christ. You look a bit rough.
-Thing is, I've decided to stay on for a bit.

541
01:19:18,759 --> 01:19:22,054
I'm meeting someone,
and I'm always keeping her waiting.

542
01:19:22,137 --> 01:19:25,724
Now, listen. Listen to me, guv'nor.

543
01:19:26,350 --> 01:19:30,604
I went out for a Jimmy Riddle just now.
Guess what I saw!

544
01:19:31,188 --> 01:19:34,399
They're getting themselves sorted out
down on the beach.

545
01:19:34,691 --> 01:19:39,488
The boats are back, and a geezer from
the Buffs is marching us down at 7:00.

546
01:19:40,447 --> 01:19:43,784
We're away. We're off home, mate.

547
01:19:46,286 --> 01:19:50,082
So get some more sleep, and no more
of your bleeding shouting.

548
01:19:50,165 --> 01:19:54,378
-All right?
-I won't say a word.

549
01:19:57,214 --> 01:20:00,050
Wake me before 7:00, would you?
Thanks so much.

550
01:20:02,427 --> 01:20:07,432
You won't hear another word
from me. Promise.

551
01:20:12,146 --> 01:20:15,774
London
Three weeks earlier

552
01:20:57,274 --> 01:20:59,902
Bed castors should be lined up
and pointing inwards.

553
01:20:59,985 --> 01:21:03,197
I found three yesterday that weren't.
You know who you are.

554
01:21:03,280 --> 01:21:05,616
Which of you were responsible
for putting away the blankets today?

555
01:21:05,699 --> 01:21:07,743
I was, Sister.
-I don't suppose you can tell us

556
01:21:07,826 --> 01:21:09,286
-what you did wrong?
-No, Sister.

557
01:21:09,369 --> 01:21:11,163
Labels are folded to the inside,
are they not?

558
01:21:11,246 --> 01:21:12,664
-Yes, Sister.
-Do them again.

559
01:21:12,748 --> 01:21:17,085
Nurse Tallis, I'll see you in my office.
The rest of you are excused.

560
01:21:30,015 --> 01:21:33,185
-ls this job at all important to you, Tallis?
-Very important, Sister.

561
01:21:33,268 --> 01:21:35,479
Yesterday, you were seconded
to men's surgical.

562
01:21:35,562 --> 01:21:38,565
When your patient came round from his
anaesthetic, it seems the first thing he did

563
01:21:38,649 --> 01:21:41,109
was to ask for Briony.
Who might Briony be?

564
01:21:41,193 --> 01:21:44,363
-Well, me, Sister.
-There is no Briony.

565
01:21:44,446 --> 01:21:47,908
You are Tallis. Nurse Tallis.
Is that understood?

566
01:21:47,991 --> 01:21:49,159
Yes, Sister.

567
01:21:59,294 --> 01:22:00,796
There is no Briony.

568
01:22:05,008 --> 01:22:08,595
This is the BBC
Home Service. Here is the news.

569
01:22:08,679 --> 01:22:12,141
The BEF, with their French allies,
are fighting a desperate battle

570
01:22:12,224 --> 01:22:14,560
in the northern zone of the Western Front.

571
01:22:14,643 --> 01:22:19,064
The Allied Forces have not lost
cohesion, and their morale is high.

572
01:22:19,148 --> 01:22:22,025
The RAF continues to give all the support
in its power

573
01:22:22,109 --> 01:22:25,362
to the Allied armies in northeastern
France and Belgium. Railways, roads,

574
01:22:25,445 --> 01:22:29,283
bridges and enemy troops have been
continuously attacked, yesterday...

575
01:22:46,592 --> 01:22:49,887
Thanks. I never could make the scissors
work with my left hand.

576
01:22:49,970 --> 01:22:52,097
Mummy always did it for me.

577
01:22:53,474 --> 01:22:55,267
There, you're done.

578
01:22:59,771 --> 01:23:00,856
Bother!

579
01:23:07,321 --> 01:23:08,363
Night-night, Ponty.

580
01:23:09,781 --> 01:23:11,575
Good night, Tallis.

581
01:23:26,882 --> 01:23:29,218
Don't panic! It's only me.

582
01:23:29,301 --> 01:23:33,013
Fiona, I almost jumped out of my skin.

583
01:23:33,806 --> 01:23:36,809
So this is where you duck to after lights out.

584
01:23:36,892 --> 01:23:41,104
I thought you might be in the middle
of some tempestuous romance.

585
01:23:41,480 --> 01:23:44,191
Don't you freeze to death up here?

586
01:23:46,610 --> 01:23:48,237
I love London.

587
01:23:49,947 --> 01:23:52,324
Do you think all of this will be
bombed and just disappear?

588
01:23:52,407 --> 01:23:53,492
No.

589
01:23:55,118 --> 01:23:56,703
I don't know.

590
01:23:57,621 --> 01:23:59,915
Do you write about Sister Drummond?

591
01:24:00,791 --> 01:24:03,126
-Do you write about me?
-Sometimes.

592
01:24:04,336 --> 01:24:07,840
-Can I look?
-I'd rather you didn't. It's private.

593
01:24:08,674 --> 01:24:12,302
I don't see any point in writing a story
if you're not going to let anyone read it.

594
01:24:12,386 --> 01:24:14,847
-It's not ready yet. It's unfinished.
-What's it about?

595
01:24:21,478 --> 01:24:24,481
-It's complicated.
-Yes?

596
01:24:24,565 --> 01:24:25,774
It's just...

597
01:24:28,235 --> 01:24:33,198
It's about a young girl, a young and
foolish girl, who sees something from

598
01:24:33,282 --> 01:24:37,828
her bedroom window which she doesn't
understand, but she thinks she does.

599
01:24:41,456 --> 01:24:43,625
I probably won't ever finish it.

600
01:24:44,251 --> 01:24:47,421
I look at you, Tallis,
and you're so mysterious.

601
01:24:48,088 --> 01:24:50,507
I've never been mysterious.

602
01:24:52,217 --> 01:24:55,012
-Do you know what I decided tonight?
-What?

603
01:24:57,473 --> 01:25:01,059
I could never marry a man
who wasn't in the Royal Navy.

604
01:25:10,736 --> 01:25:13,530
Here we are. Cecilia Tallis.

605
01:25:14,031 --> 01:25:16,200
I think this is her address.

606
01:25:18,243 --> 01:25:19,411
Thank you.

607
01:25:28,420 --> 01:25:32,174
Dear Cecilia. Please don't
throw this away without reading it.

608
01:25:33,300 --> 01:25:35,803
As you'll have seen from the
notepaper, I'm here at St Thomas'

609
01:25:35,886 --> 01:25:38,138
doing my nurses' training.

610
01:25:38,222 --> 01:25:40,724
I decided not to take up
my place at Cambridge.

611
01:25:40,808 --> 01:25:42,184
Oh, God.

612
01:25:43,852 --> 01:25:47,648
I decided I wanted to make myself useful.
Do something practical.

613
01:25:50,400 --> 01:25:53,445
It says in the newspaper
the Army are making strategic withdrawals.

614
01:25:53,529 --> 01:25:54,613
Yes, I saw that.

615
01:25:54,696 --> 01:25:56,740
It's a euphemism for retreat.

616
01:25:58,075 --> 01:26:01,787
No matter how hard I work,
no matter how long the hours,

617
01:26:02,704 --> 01:26:05,165
I can't escape from what I did

618
01:26:05,249 --> 01:26:08,293
and what it meant,

619
01:26:08,377 --> 01:26:12,089
the full extent of which
I am only now beginning to grasp.

620
01:26:19,054 --> 01:26:22,015
Cee, please write and tell me we can meet.

621
01:26:23,767 --> 01:26:25,602
Your sister, Briony.

622
01:26:27,938 --> 01:26:30,816
So do you?
-Do I what?

623
01:26:31,233 --> 01:26:35,529
Have a secret fiancé in France.
That's what everyone thinks.

624
01:26:35,612 --> 01:26:36,655
No, of course not.

625
01:26:36,738 --> 01:26:39,324
Imagine not knowing if he'd ever come back.

626
01:26:39,408 --> 01:26:41,577
I've never been in love.

627
01:26:42,327 --> 01:26:45,038
What, never? Not even a crush?

628
01:26:45,706 --> 01:26:49,168
Oh, I had a crush once, when I was 10 or 11.

629
01:26:51,378 --> 01:26:54,715
I jumped into a river to see
if he'd save me from drowning.

630
01:26:54,798 --> 01:26:58,302
-Now you're teasing me.
-Oh, no. And he did save me.

631
01:27:01,305 --> 01:27:04,975
But as soon as I told him I loved him,
the feeling sort of disappeared.

632
01:27:05,058 --> 01:27:06,643
Something's happened.

633
01:27:11,106 --> 01:27:12,608
Outside, quickly.

634
01:27:56,777 --> 01:27:58,028
Robbie.

635
01:28:02,074 --> 01:28:03,158
Excuse me.

636
01:28:52,833 --> 01:28:56,295
Nurse Tallis, you speak a little French,
if I remember rightly.

637
01:28:56,378 --> 01:28:57,629
Only school French, Sister.

638
01:28:57,713 --> 01:29:02,050
There's a soldier in Bed 13. Go and sit
with him for a minute. Hold his hand.

639
01:29:02,134 --> 01:29:03,260
Off you go.

640
01:29:57,231 --> 01:29:58,732
Here you are at last

641
01:29:59,608 --> 01:30:01,235
Sister sent me

642
01:30:01,318 --> 01:30:03,570
for a little chat

643
01:30:06,406 --> 01:30:08,659
I remember your sister

644
01:30:09,159 --> 01:30:11,703
she was always so nice

645
01:30:13,413 --> 01:30:14,998
what's she doing now?

646
01:30:16,875 --> 01:30:20,212
She is a nurse as well

647
01:30:21,255 --> 01:30:24,383
Did she finally marry that man
she was so in love with?

648
01:30:25,050 --> 01:30:26,468
I've forgotten his name

649
01:30:26,552 --> 01:30:27,636
Robbie?

650
01:30:29,388 --> 01:30:30,889
She will soon I hope

651
01:30:31,849 --> 01:30:32,933
Robbie

652
01:30:33,559 --> 01:30:35,394
yes that's right

653
01:30:37,688 --> 01:30:38,772
And you?

654
01:30:39,106 --> 01:30:40,649
What is your name?

655
01:30:42,860 --> 01:30:43,902
Luc.

656
01:30:45,404 --> 01:30:46,822
Luc Cornet.

657
01:30:49,032 --> 01:30:50,284
And you?

658
01:30:50,367 --> 01:30:51,451
Tallis.

659
01:30:52,870 --> 01:30:53,912
Tallis.

660
01:30:55,747 --> 01:30:57,666
That's pretty

661
01:31:02,588 --> 01:31:05,215
I remember you now

662
01:31:07,176 --> 01:31:09,303
the English girl

663
01:31:10,512 --> 01:31:13,307
You remember your first visit to Millau?

664
01:31:14,641 --> 01:31:17,186
I was working by the ovens with my father.

665
01:31:18,187 --> 01:31:20,355
I heard your accent

666
01:31:24,485 --> 01:31:27,237
Can you do me a little favour Tallis?

667
01:31:29,156 --> 01:31:31,825
These bandages are so tight,

668
01:31:32,159 --> 01:31:35,287
can you loosen them a bit, please?

669
01:31:36,413 --> 01:31:37,831
Of course

670
01:31:45,714 --> 01:31:48,050
You remember my younger sister, Anne?

671
01:31:50,469 --> 01:31:53,514
She still plays that little Debussy piece

672
01:31:55,265 --> 01:31:56,683
do you remember?

673
01:31:59,061 --> 01:32:02,147
She looks so serious when she plays

674
01:32:03,273 --> 01:32:05,150
And our croissants,

675
01:32:05,776 --> 01:32:07,611
what did you think of them?

676
01:32:15,244 --> 01:32:17,412
The most delicious in Millau

677
01:32:17,830 --> 01:32:18,872
Yes.

678
01:32:19,081 --> 01:32:21,208
it's the quality of the butter

679
01:32:22,918 --> 01:32:23,961
Yes

680
01:32:27,464 --> 01:32:29,925
Is that why you came every day?

681
01:32:31,385 --> 01:32:32,970
Because you know,

682
01:32:34,930 --> 01:32:38,392
my mother is very fond of you

683
01:32:39,101 --> 01:32:40,811
in her opinion,

684
01:32:41,311 --> 01:32:44,064
we should get married in the summer

685
01:32:44,439 --> 01:32:45,899
Oh yes?

686
01:32:46,150 --> 01:32:47,651
Yes

687
01:32:55,617 --> 01:32:57,995
I hope that's more comfortable

688
01:33:02,916 --> 01:33:03,959
Do you love me?

689
01:33:04,042 --> 01:33:06,044
Yes

690
01:33:14,428 --> 01:33:16,889
Can you stay a while?

691
01:33:18,390 --> 01:33:21,435
I'm frightened

692
01:33:30,777 --> 01:33:32,404
-Tallis.
-Briony.

693
01:33:34,156 --> 01:33:35,949
Je m'appelle Briony.

694
01:33:47,795 --> 01:33:49,880
Stand up, Nurse Tallis.

695
01:33:54,843 --> 01:33:57,596
Now go and wash the blood off your face.

696
01:34:59,449 --> 01:35:04,413
The Navy has earned our
undying gratitude. The Army is undefeated.

697
01:35:04,496 --> 01:35:08,250
Courage has brought them through
unconquered, their spirit unbowed.

698
01:35:08,333 --> 01:35:10,419
This is the epic of Dunkirk.

699
01:35:10,502 --> 01:35:14,756
A name that will live forever
in the annals of warfare.

700
01:35:18,510 --> 01:35:20,721
In the course of a comprehensive tour,

701
01:35:20,804 --> 01:35:24,558
Queen Elizabeth is seen here visiting
a chocolate factory in the north of England.

702
01:35:24,641 --> 01:35:26,977
The confectionary magnate
and friend of the British Army,

703
01:35:27,060 --> 01:35:31,315
Mr Paul Marshall, gave the Queen a tour
of the Army Amo factory

704
01:35:31,398 --> 01:35:35,777
with his lovely,
soon-to-be-wed fiancée, Miss Lola Quincey.

705
01:35:35,861 --> 01:35:38,614
What a mouthwatering couple they are.

706
01:35:38,739 --> 01:35:42,284
Keep the Amo coming.
Our boys have a sweet tooth.

707
01:36:09,895 --> 01:36:15,859
Secondly, for a remedy against sin,
and to avoid fornication,

708
01:36:15,943 --> 01:36:19,822
that such persons
as have not the gift of continence,

709
01:36:19,905 --> 01:36:25,494
might marry and keep themselves
undefiled members of Christ's body.

710
01:36:26,328 --> 01:36:31,542
Thirdly, it was ordained,
for the mutual society, help and comfort,

711
01:36:31,625 --> 01:36:35,170
that the one ought to have the other.

712
01:36:35,254 --> 01:36:36,380
I saw him.

713
01:36:36,463 --> 01:36:40,384
Therefore, if any man can show
any just cause

714
01:36:40,467 --> 01:36:43,428
why they may not be
lawfully joined together...

715
01:36:43,595 --> 01:36:44,638
I know it was him.

716
01:36:44,888 --> 01:36:50,352
...Iet him now speak
or forever hold his peace.

717
01:36:56,942 --> 01:36:59,653
I saw him. I saw him with my own eyes.

718
01:37:42,070 --> 01:37:43,780
Let the nursey through.

719
01:37:43,864 --> 01:37:46,366
They're going down to the country today.
Never been out of London before.

720
01:37:46,450 --> 01:37:47,659
I hope they get a nice family.

721
01:37:47,743 --> 01:37:49,995
They don't know what they're in for
with this lot.

722
01:37:50,078 --> 01:37:51,163
Come on.

723
01:38:09,264 --> 01:38:12,351
I'm looking for Miss Tallis. Cecilia Tallis.

724
01:38:13,769 --> 01:38:14,853
Is she in?

725
01:38:20,984 --> 01:38:23,487
Tallis! Door!

726
01:38:31,286 --> 01:38:33,539
I tried writing. You wouldn't answer.

727
01:38:38,544 --> 01:38:40,420
I have to talk to you.

728
01:39:05,070 --> 01:39:07,447
-So you're a ward sister now?
-Yes.

729
01:39:20,836 --> 01:39:21,920
Thanks.

730
01:39:31,305 --> 01:39:33,348
I want to go in front of a judge
and change my evidence, Cee.

731
01:39:33,432 --> 01:39:35,142
Don't call me that.

732
01:39:40,772 --> 01:39:42,774
Please don't call me that.

733
01:39:45,736 --> 01:39:48,113
I know what I did was terrible.
I don't expect you to forgive me.

734
01:39:48,197 --> 01:39:50,240
Oh, don't worry, I won't.

735
01:39:52,367 --> 01:39:54,912
You're an unreliable witness.
They'll never reopen the case.

736
01:39:54,995 --> 01:39:56,747
Well, at least
I could tell everyone else what I did.

737
01:39:56,830 --> 01:39:59,249
I can go home and explain
to Mummy and Daddy and Leon...

738
01:39:59,333 --> 01:40:01,585
-So what's stopping you?
-Well, I wanted to see you first.

739
01:40:01,668 --> 01:40:03,879
They don't want to hear any more about it.

740
01:40:03,962 --> 01:40:07,174
That unpleasantness is all tidied away
in the past, thank you very much.

741
01:40:07,257 --> 01:40:08,383
But...

742
01:40:16,391 --> 01:40:18,644
I'll be late. Better get moving.

743
01:40:22,189 --> 01:40:23,524
Excuse me.

744
01:40:29,905 --> 01:40:31,782
He sleeps so deeply.

745
01:41:32,050 --> 01:41:35,387
-What is she doing here?
-She wanted to speak to me.

746
01:41:35,471 --> 01:41:37,347
Oh, yes, what about?

747
01:41:37,431 --> 01:41:38,807
The terrible thing I did.

748
01:41:38,891 --> 01:41:40,392
Robbie. Darling.

749
01:41:44,396 --> 01:41:46,398
I'll be quite honest with you.

750
01:41:46,482 --> 01:41:47,941
I'm torn between breaking your neck here

751
01:41:48,025 --> 01:41:51,028
and taking you
and throwing you down the stairs.

752
01:41:51,111 --> 01:41:52,237
Oh, God.

753
01:41:52,321 --> 01:41:56,408
Do you have any idea what it's like in jail?
Of course, you don't.

754
01:41:56,783 --> 01:41:59,369
Tell me, did it give you pleasure
to think of me inside?

755
01:41:59,453 --> 01:42:01,288
-No.
-But you did nothing about it.

756
01:42:01,371 --> 01:42:03,081
-No.
-Do you think I assaulted your cousin?

757
01:42:03,165 --> 01:42:04,249
-No.
-Did you think it then?

758
01:42:04,333 --> 01:42:05,417
Yes. But yes and no.

759
01:42:05,501 --> 01:42:07,419
-And what's made you so certain now?
-Growing up.

760
01:42:07,503 --> 01:42:09,046
-Growing up?
-I was 13.

761
01:42:09,129 --> 01:42:12,299
How old do you have to be to know
the difference between right and wrong?

762
01:42:12,382 --> 01:42:13,801
What are you, 18?

763
01:42:13,884 --> 01:42:16,762
Do you have to be 18 before
you can bring yourself to own up to a lie?

764
01:42:16,845 --> 01:42:20,933
There are soldiers of 18, old enough
to be left to die by the side of the road,

765
01:42:21,016 --> 01:42:22,434
-did you know that?
-Yes.

766
01:42:22,518 --> 01:42:24,812
Five years ago,
you didn't care about telling the truth.

767
01:42:24,895 --> 01:42:28,232
You, all your family, you just assumed
that for all my education,

768
01:42:28,315 --> 01:42:31,443
I was still little better than a servant.
Still not to be trusted!

769
01:42:31,527 --> 01:42:34,571
Thanks to you, they were able to close ranks
and throw me to the fucking wolves!

770
01:42:34,655 --> 01:42:37,658
-Robbie! Look at me, look at me.
-Don't!

771
01:42:37,741 --> 01:42:41,370
Come back. Come back.

772
01:42:43,914 --> 01:42:46,166
Come back to me.

773
01:43:10,190 --> 01:43:11,275
Briony.

774
01:43:13,152 --> 01:43:14,862
There isn't much time.

775
01:43:16,113 --> 01:43:19,867
Robbie has to report for duty at 6:00,
and he's got a train to catch.

776
01:43:21,535 --> 01:43:22,870
So sit down.

777
01:43:28,792 --> 01:43:31,545
There are some things
you're going to do for us.

778
01:43:48,353 --> 01:43:50,105
You'll go to your parents
as soon as you can,

779
01:43:50,189 --> 01:43:51,565
and you'll tell them everything
they need to know

780
01:43:51,648 --> 01:43:54,693
to be convinced
that the evidence you gave was false.

781
01:43:54,776 --> 01:43:56,445
You'll meet with a solicitor,
make a statement,

782
01:43:56,528 --> 01:43:58,697
have it signed, witnessed,
send copies to us. Is that clear?

783
01:43:58,780 --> 01:43:59,907
Yes.

784
01:43:59,990 --> 01:44:02,826
You'll write a detailed letter to me
explaining everything that happened

785
01:44:02,910 --> 01:44:04,912
leading up to you saying
you saw me by the lake.

786
01:44:04,995 --> 01:44:06,246
Try to include whatever you can remember

787
01:44:06,330 --> 01:44:08,123
of what Danny Hardman was doing
that night.

788
01:44:08,207 --> 01:44:09,458
-Hardman?
-Yes.

789
01:44:12,669 --> 01:44:14,338
It wasn't Danny Hardman.

790
01:44:15,214 --> 01:44:17,216
It was Leon's friend, Marshall.

791
01:44:18,050 --> 01:44:19,134
I don't believe you.

792
01:44:19,218 --> 01:44:22,471
He's married Lola.
I've just come from their wedding.

793
01:44:28,477 --> 01:44:31,146
Lola won't be able to testify
against him now.

794
01:44:33,565 --> 01:44:34,983
He's immune.

795
01:44:50,749 --> 01:44:55,504
I'm very, very sorry for the terrible distress
that I have caused.

796
01:44:57,506 --> 01:44:59,758
I am very, very sorry.

797
01:45:00,300 --> 01:45:02,302
Just do as we've asked of you.

798
01:45:02,678 --> 01:45:07,141
Write it all down, just the truth, no rhymes.
No embellishments, no adjectives.

799
01:45:08,892 --> 01:45:10,644
And then leave us be.

800
01:45:12,563 --> 01:45:13,981
I will, I promise.

801
01:46:16,794 --> 01:46:19,004
I'm sorry.
Could we stop for a moment?

802
01:46:20,380 --> 01:46:22,007
Of course. Is something the matter?

803
01:46:22,090 --> 01:46:25,344
I just need a couple of minutes by myself.

804
01:46:27,721 --> 01:46:29,556
...minutes by myself.

805
01:46:30,974 --> 01:46:36,355
Briony Tallis, your new novel,
your twenty-first, is called Atonement. It's...

806
01:46:38,232 --> 01:46:39,316
Briony?

807
01:46:44,530 --> 01:46:46,740
I'm sorry. Could we stop for a moment?

808
01:47:21,984 --> 01:47:26,155
Briony Tallis, I'd like to talk now
about your new novel, Atonement,

809
01:47:26,238 --> 01:47:29,825
which comes out in a few days
to coincide with your birthday.

810
01:47:30,409 --> 01:47:34,830
-It's your twenty-first novel...
-It's my last novel.

811
01:47:36,373 --> 01:47:38,959
Oh, really? Are you retiring?

812
01:47:40,169 --> 01:47:41,503
I'm dying.

813
01:47:43,714 --> 01:47:47,926
My doctor tells me
I have something called vascular dementia,

814
01:47:49,553 --> 01:47:52,639
which is essentially
a continuous series of tiny strokes.

815
01:47:52,723 --> 01:47:58,353
Your brain closes down, gradually
you lose words, you lose your memory,

816
01:47:58,437 --> 01:48:01,482
which for a writer is pretty much the point.

817
01:48:04,318 --> 01:48:08,947
So that's why I could finally write the book,
I think. I had to.

818
01:48:09,781 --> 01:48:12,117
And why, of course, it's my last novel.

819
01:48:15,329 --> 01:48:16,872
Strangely enough,

820
01:48:21,752 --> 01:48:26,089
it would be just as accurate
to call it my first novel.

821
01:48:27,257 --> 01:48:32,471
I wrote several drafts as far back as my time
at St Thomas' Hospital during the War.

822
01:48:33,263 --> 01:48:35,766
I just couldn't ever find the way to do it.

823
01:48:36,558 --> 01:48:39,019
Because the novel is autobiographical,
is that right?

824
01:48:39,102 --> 01:48:42,606
Yes, entirely. I haven't changed any names,
including my own.

825
01:48:42,689 --> 01:48:44,525
And was that the problem?

826
01:48:45,859 --> 01:48:46,985
No.

827
01:48:47,861 --> 01:48:52,616
I had, for a very long time,
decided to tell the absolute truth.

828
01:48:54,117 --> 01:48:56,286
No rhymes, no embellishments.

829
01:49:05,295 --> 01:49:06,630
And I think...

830
01:49:09,675 --> 01:49:12,302
You've read the book,
you'll understand why.

831
01:49:14,304 --> 01:49:18,559
I got first-hand accounts of all the events
I didn't personally witness,

832
01:49:19,184 --> 01:49:24,148
the conditions in prison,
the evacuation to Dunkirk, everything.

833
01:49:25,649 --> 01:49:28,861
But the effect of all this honesty
was rather pitiless.

834
01:49:28,944 --> 01:49:35,033
You see, I couldn't any longer imagine
what purpose would be served by it.

835
01:49:36,535 --> 01:49:39,121
By what? Sorry. Served by honesty?

836
01:49:39,204 --> 01:49:40,330
By honesty.

837
01:49:41,707 --> 01:49:43,041
Or reality.

838
01:49:48,505 --> 01:49:50,382
Because, in fact,

839
01:49:51,717 --> 01:49:56,430
I was too much of a coward
to go and see my sister in June, 1940.

840
01:49:58,223 --> 01:50:00,017
I never made that journey to Balham.

841
01:50:00,100 --> 01:50:01,768
Do you have any idea
what it's like in jail?

842
01:50:01,852 --> 01:50:03,896
So the scene in which
I confess to them is imagined.

843
01:50:03,979 --> 01:50:05,105
He sleeps so deeply.

844
01:50:05,189 --> 01:50:06,231
Invented.

845
01:50:06,315 --> 01:50:09,234
How old do you have to be to know
the difference between right and wrong?

846
01:50:09,318 --> 01:50:11,778
And, in fact,
could never have happened.

847
01:50:11,862 --> 01:50:12,946
Because

848
01:50:15,365 --> 01:50:20,287
Robbie Turner died of septicaemia
at Bray-Dunes

849
01:50:21,413 --> 01:50:23,749
on June the first, 1940,

850
01:50:24,792 --> 01:50:26,877
the last day of the evacuation.

851
01:50:31,757 --> 01:50:32,966
Cheerio, pal.

852
01:51:06,792 --> 01:51:10,838
And I was never able to put things right
with my sister, Cecilia,

853
01:51:12,589 --> 01:51:17,177
because she was killed
on the 15th of October, 1940,

854
01:51:17,511 --> 01:51:21,849
by the bomb that destroyed the gas
and water mains above Balham tube station.

855
01:51:58,594 --> 01:51:59,678
So...

856
01:52:02,222 --> 01:52:05,934
My sister and Robbie were never able
to have the time together

857
01:52:07,519 --> 01:52:11,648
they both so longed for, and deserved.

858
01:52:13,442 --> 01:52:16,320
And which, ever since, I've...

859
01:52:21,408 --> 01:52:25,662
Ever since I've always felt I prevented.

860
01:52:32,252 --> 01:52:35,380
But what sense of hope,

861
01:52:36,965 --> 01:52:41,428
or satisfaction, could a reader derive
from an ending like that?

862
01:52:42,262 --> 01:52:48,811
So, in the book, I wanted to give Robbie
and Cecilia what they lost out on in life.

863
01:52:50,187 --> 01:52:55,442
I'd like to think
this isn't weakness or evasion,

864
01:52:58,070 --> 01:53:00,197
but a final act of kindness.

865
01:53:01,990 --> 01:53:08,747
I gave them their happiness.

866
